    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided preamble chunks, here are the disclosed customer types, contract descriptions, and details regarding government/commercial contracts and customer concentration for each segment:\n\n### 1. Launch (Space Segment)\n*   **Customer Types:** Commercial and government customers. Named clients include NASA, the National Reconnaissance Office (NRO), Axiom Space, SES, Eutelsat, and Oneweb. SpaceX is noted as the primary launch provider for the U.S. government.\n*   **Contract Descriptions:** Customers are charged based on the type of rocket, mass to orbit, size of payload, and type of service (e.g., dedicated launch vs. "rideshare"). \n    *   *Launch Services:* Fixed-price contracts ranging from 1 to 5 years. Revenue is recognized at a point in time (upon launch or deployment of the payload).\n    *   *Launch and Development:* Fixed-price contracts ranging from 1 to 14 years for the development of spacecraft and provision of mission services. Revenue is recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method.\n*   **Government Contracts:** In 2025, SpaceX launched 11 of 12 National Security Space Launch (NSSL) medium and heavy lift missions and all five U.S. crew and cargo missions to the International Space Station for NASA.\n*   **Customer Concentration:** Specific concentration metrics are not disclosed, but the text notes that inter-segment launch costs for Starlink satellites are capitalized and not recognized as revenue; Space segment revenue only reflects external customer launches.\n\n### 2. Starlink (Connectivity Segment)\n*   **Consumer:**\n    *   **Customer Types:** Individual residential users (households and personal use) and small-to-medium-sized businesses (defined as "Starlink Subscribers").\n    *   **Contract Descriptions:** Monthly subscription fees based on geographic market and download speed, plus typically a one-time upfront terminal kit cost. Revenue is recognized ratably over the service period. In 2025, consumer subscribers represented over 60% of Connectivity segment revenue.\n*   **Enterprise:**\n    *   **Customer Types:** Broad fixed-site customer base across industries requiring high availability (retail, financial services), as well as construction, agriculture, telecom, hospitality, aviation, maritime, and land mobility. Named enterprise customers include United Airlines, Carnival, Maersk, and John Deere.\n    *   **Contract Descriptions:** Contracts are structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, capacity, or other pricing models (including percentage-of-completion) depending on the customer’s needs.\n    *   **Customer Concentration/Retention:** High retention is noted; since 2023, no Starlink Enterprise customer contributing more than $750,000 of annual revenue has voluntarily discontinued service.\n*   **Government Solutions:**\n    *   **Customer Types:** Government entities and public institutions (e.g., FEMA, NOAA, and the Governments of the Philippines, Jamaica, and Ecuador).\n    *   **Contract Descriptions:** High-speed, resilient connectivity for public services, social impact, humanitarian efforts, and disaster response in remote and challenging environments.\n*   **Starlink Mobile:**\n    *   **Customer Types:** Consumers, businesses, and public-sector customers accessed via partnerships with Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) such as T-Mobile, One NZ, Optus, Telstra, Rogers, KDDI, Salt, Entel, Kyivstar, and VMO2.\n    *   **Contract Descriptions:** Satellite-to-mobile connectivity supplementing terrestrial networks. SpaceX charges MNOs either a fixed fee or a per-mobile user fee-based amount. Revenue is earned through revenue-sharing arrangements with MNO partners based on connectivity services included in their plans.\n\n### 3. Starshield (Connectivity Segment - Government)\n*   **Customer Types:** United States Government customers and national security applications.\n*   **Contract Descriptions:** Secure, dedicated satellite network leveraging commercial LEO learnings. Revenue is generated via long-term contracts. Starshield is focused on three core mission areas: Earth observation, global secure communications, and hosted payloads. It features high-assurance cryptographic capabilities tailored to military requirements, allowing government customers to deploy mission-specific capabilities in LEO without building standalone spacecraft.\n\n### 4. xAI (AI Segment)\n*   **Customer Types:** Consumer and enterprise customers.\n*   **Contract Descriptions:** Operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning gigawatt-scale AI compute infrastructure (including COLOSSUS and COLOSSUS II clusters) and the frontier LLM Grok. Revenue falls under "AI Solutions & Infrastructure." Specific contract lengths or pricing models for xAI are not detailed in the provided text.\n\n### 5. X (AI Segment)\n*   **Customer Types:** Users of the real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform.\n*   **Contract Descriptions:** Revenue is generated through "Advertising." Specific contract descriptions, pricing models, or customer concentration metrics for X are not detailed in the provided text.',
