    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Starshield Disclosures: Revenue, Customer Concentration, and Government Contracts\n\n## 1. Starshield Revenue Classification and Recognition\n\n**Segment classification**: Starshield revenue is **not broken out separately**. It is included within the **Connectivity segment**, specifically under the **"Enterprise & Government"** revenue category (which also includes Starlink Mobile service offerings). The filing explicitly footnotes: *"Enterprise & Government revenue includes revenue from Starlink Mobile service offerings."*\n\n**Revenue recognition policy**: Starshield contracts are recognized **over time** using the **cost-to-cost input method**, because they are multi-year, fixed-price development contracts. The filing states:\n\n> *"The Company recognizes revenue over time for certain contracts related to our Starshield business that are multi-year in nature. For revenue that is recognized over time, we use the cost-to-cost input method."*\n\nRevenue is recorded based on costs (materials and labor hours) incurred to date relative to total estimated cost at completion. These contracts are described as "complex" and requiring "significant management judgment," including assumptions about labor hours, shared-cost allocation, satellite material costs, and expected technological changes.\n\n## 2. Size of Starshield Revenue vs. Other Segments\n\n**No standalone Starshield revenue figure is disclosed.** The filing does not separately quantify Starshield revenue. What can be inferred:\n\n| Segment / Category | 2025 Revenue Context |\n|---|---|\n| **Total consolidated revenue** | $18,674 million |\n| **Space segment** | $4,086 million |\n| **Connectivity segment (total)** | Substantial majority of remaining revenue (~$14B+ implied) |\n| — Consumer subscribers | **>60% of Connectivity segment revenue** |\n| — Enterprise & Government (incl. Starshield + Starlink Mobile) | <40% of Connectivity segment revenue |\n| **AI segment** | Not separately quantified in the excerpts |\n\nSince consumer subscribers represent over 60% of Connectivity revenue, the entire Enterprise & Government category (which bundles Starshield with Starlink Mobile and other enterprise revenue) is a minority of Connectivity segment revenue. **Starshield alone is therefore a small subset of an already sub-40% portion of the Connectivity segment**, suggesting it is not yet a material standalone revenue contributor relative to consumer Starlink or the Space segment.\n\n## 3. Customer Concentration Disclosures\n\nThe filing discloses **one significant customer** ("Customer A") but does **not** identify whether this customer is a Starshield customer specifically:\n\n| Year | Customer A % of Consolidated Revenue |\n|---|---|\n| 2025 | 20.9% |\n| 2024 | 24.2% |\n| 2023 | 25.2% |\n\nKey disclosures:\n- *"Revenue from this customer relates to all three segments."*\n- *"No other customers represented more than 10% of consolidated revenue during the years ended December 31, 2025, 2024 and 2023."*\n\nBecause Customer A spans all three segments (Space, Connectivity, AI), it likely includes Starshield-related revenue, but the filing does **not** isolate Starshield\'s contribution from this customer. There is **no quantitative disclosure of Starshield\'s largest customer** on a standalone basis.\n\n## 4. Government Contract Disclosures\n\n**Starshield-specific government disclosures**:\n- Starshield is described as *"a secure satellite network designed specifically for United States Government customers and national security applications."*\n- Three core mission areas: **Earth observation, global secure communications, and hosted payloads**.\n- Built on Starlink-derived infrastructure with added high-assurance cryptographic capabilities.\n- Contracts are **long-term** and **fixed-price**.\n\n**Other government contract references** (not exclusively Starshield):\n- **NASA Cargo Resupply Services (CRS)** — additional missions to the ISS, cited as partially offsetting Starship R&D drag on Space segment EBITDA.\n- **U.S. Department of War contract** — cited as increased revenue partially offsetting Starship investment drag.\n- **International government customers** for Starlink (not Starshield): Philippines (remote islands, schools), Jamaica (remote/maritime digital access), Ecuador (education and healthcare connectivity), plus FEMA and NOAA domestically.\n\n## 5. Backlog and Deferred Revenue (Government-Contract-Heavy)\n\nBacklog and deferred revenue are the closest proxies for Starshield\'s forward revenue visibility, though they are not Starshield-specific:\n\n| Metric | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| **Total backlog (Dec 31, 2025)** | $28,377 million |\n| — Recognized as deferred revenue | $12,116 million |\n| — Expected within 1 year | ~32% (~$9.1B) |\n| — Expected in 2027–2028 | ~53% (~$15.0B) |\n| — Thereafter | ~15% (~$4.3B) |\n| **Total deferred revenue (Dec 31, 2025)** | $12,116 million |\n| **Total deferred revenue (Dec 31, 2024)** | $10,179 million |\n| — Recognized as revenue in 2025 | $4,080 million |\n\nThe filing states deferred revenue *"primarily relates to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise and government contracts"* — which would encompass Starshield. The long-tail recognition profile (53% in 2027–2028) is consistent with multi-year fixed-price government development contracts like Starshield.\n\n## Summary of Key Takeaways\n\n1. **Starshield revenue is not separately quantified** — it is embedded within Connectivity\'s "Enterprise & Government" category, which itself is less than 40% of Connectivity segment revenue.\n2. **No standalone Starshield customer concentration disclosure exists.** The only disclosed significant customer (Customer A, ~20.9% of consolidated revenue in 2025) spans all three segments but is not attributed to Starshield specifically.\n3. **Government contracts are described qualitatively** (long-term, fixed-price, cost-to-cost input method, significant judgment in cost estimation) but **not quantified** for Starshield alone.\n4. **Backlog of $28.4B and deferred revenue of $12.1B** provide indirect visibility into government/enterprise contract commitments, but these are not disaggregated to isolate Starshield.\n5. The filing emphasizes Starshield\'s **strategic importance** (national security platform, three mission areas, cryptographic capabilities) more than its **financial materiality** at present, suggesting Starshield is still in a relatively early revenue ramp phase compared to consumer Starlink and the Space launch business.',
